<worksheet xml:id="week14-handout">
  <title>Week 13-14 Handout-Integral Transforms</title>

    <introduction>
        <statement> <p>
        We will discuss the following topics related to <term> Integral Transforms (Chap 15)</term>:
      <ul>
        <li> <p>Laplace Transforms (15.2)  </p>   </li>
        <li> <p>Fourier Transforms (15.4)</p> </li>
      </ul>  </p>
        </statement>
    </introduction>
    <definition xml:id="def-laplace-transform-partial">
      <title>Laplace Transform</title>     
      <statement>The Laplace transform of <m> u(x,t)</m> with respect to <m>t</m> is defined as
        <p> <md>\mathscr{L}\left\{u(x,t)\right\}=\int_0^\infty e^{-st}u(x,t)dt=U(x,s),</md>
          where <m>x</m> is treated as a parameter.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <remark>
      <statement>
        <p> In Week 1, we used <term>Laplace Transform</term> to reduce the ODE to an algebraic equation.
          Here, we will use <term>Laplace Transform</term> to reduce a PDE to an ODE. Here are a few useful
          properties:
          <ol>
            <li> <p> <md xml:id="eq-laplace-transform-1st" number="yes">
              \mathscr{L}\left\{\frac{\partial u}{\partial t}\right\}=sU(x,s)-u(x,0)
            </md> </p> </li>
            <li><p> <md xml:id="eq-laplace-transform-2nd" number="yes">
              \mathscr{L}\left\{\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial t^2}\right\}=s^2U(x,s)-su(x,0)-u_t(x,0)
            </md>      </p>        </li>
            <li>  <p>  <md xml:id="eq-laplace-transform-2nd-x" number="yes">
              \mathscr{L}\left\{\frac{\partial ^2 u}{\partial x^2}\right\}=\frac{d^2 U}{d x^2}
            </md>
                     </p>     </li>

          </ol> 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </remark>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve the boundary value problem using Laplace Transform:
          <md>
            <mrow>\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x^2}=\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial t^2}, \amp  \amp  0\lt x\lt 1, t\gt 0 </mrow>
            <mrow>u(0,t)=0, u(1,t)=0,  \amp \amp  t\gt 0 </mrow>
            <mrow> u(x,0)=0,  \frac{\partial u}{\partial t}\biggr|_{t=0}=2\sin\pi x+4\sin 3\pi x, \amp  \amp  0\lt x\lt 1</mrow>
          </md>

        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p> Use the Laplace transform to solve the heat equation 
          <md>u_{xx}=u_t, x\gt 0,t\gt 0 </md> 
          subjec to
          <md>u(0,t)=0, u(1,t)=u_0, t\gt 0, u(x,0)=0, 0\lt x\lt 1</md>
          
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <remark>
      <statement>
        <p>Integral transforms appear in <term>transform pairs.</term> If <m>f(x)</m> is transformed into
          <m>F(\alpha)</m> by an <term>integral transform</term>
          <md xml:id="eq-integral-trans" number="yes">
            F(\alpha)=\int_a^b f(x)K(\alpha,x)dx,
          </md>
          then the function <m>f</m> can be recovered by another integral transform
          <md xml:id="eq-inverse-integral" number="yes">
            f(x)=\int_c^d F(\alpha)H(\alpha,x)d\alpha
          </md>
          called the <term>inverse transform.</term> The functions <m>K</m> and <m>H</m> in 
          <xref ref="eq-integral-trans"/> and <xref ref="eq-inverse-integral"/> are called
          <term>kernels</term> of their respective transforms.
          
          In <term>Laplace transform</term>, <m>K(s,t)=e^{-st}</m> and <m>H(s,t)=\frac{e^{st}}{2\pi i}.</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </remark>
    <definition xml:id="def-fourier-transform">
      <title>Fourier Transform Pairs</title>    
      
      <statement>
        <p><ol>
          <li>  <p>
            <ul> <li>   <p>            <term>Fourier Transform</term>: <md xml:id="eq-fourier-trans" number="yes">
            \mathscr{F}\{f(x)\}=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(x)e^{i\alpha x}dx=F(\alpha)</md>     </p> </li>
            <li><term>Inverse Fourier Transform</term>: <md xml:id="eq-inverse-fourier" number="yes">
            \mathscr{F}^{-1}\{F(\alpha)\}=\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}F(\alpha)e^{-i\alpha x}d\alpha=f(x)</md> 
              <p>
                
              </p>
            </li>
            </ul>

            </p>
          </li>
          <li>  <p>
            <ul> <li>   <p>            <term>Fourier cosine Transform</term>: <md xml:id="eq-fourier-cos" number="yes">
            \mathscr{F}_c\{f(x)\}=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(x)\cos(\alpha x)dx=F(\alpha)</md>     </p> </li>
            <li><term>Inverse Fourier cosine Transform</term>: <md xml:id="eq-inverse-fourier-cos" number="yes">
            \mathscr{F}_c^{-1}\{F(\alpha)\}=\frac{2}{\pi}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}F(\alpha)\cos(\alpha x)d\alpha=f(x)</md> 
              <p>
                
              </p>
            </li>
            </ul>

            </p>
          </li>
                    <li>  <p>
            <ul> <li>   <p>            <term>Fourier sine Transform</term>: <md xml:id="eq-fourier-sin" number="yes">
            \mathscr{F}_s\{f(x)\}=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(x)\sin(\alpha x)dx=F(\alpha)</md>     </p> </li>
            <li><term>Inverse Fourier sine Transform</term>: <md xml:id="eq-inverse-fourier-sin" number="yes">
            \mathscr{F}_s^{-1}\{F(\alpha)\}=\frac{2}{\pi}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}F(\alpha)\sin(\alpha x)d\alpha=f(x)</md> 
              <p>
                
              </p>
            </li>
            </ul>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol> 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <remark>
      <title>Existence and Properties of Fourier Transform</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <ul>
            <li><p> Sufficient conditions for existence of <xref ref="eq-fourier-trans"/>, 
              <xref ref="eq-fourier-cos"/>, and <xref ref="eq-fourier-sin"/> are that 
              <m>f</m> be <term>absolutely integrable</term> on the appropriate interval
              and that <m>f</m> and <m>f'</m> be <term>piecewise continuous on every finite interval.</term>
              </p>  </li>
            <li><p> <m>\mathscr{F}\{1\},</m> <m>\mathscr{F}_c\{1\}</m>, and <m>\mathscr{F}_s\{1\}</m> <term> do not exist.</term>
              </p> </li>
            <li><p>All 6 transforms in <xref ref="def-fourier-transform"/> are <term>linear transforms.</term>    </p>   </li>
            <li><p> Suppose that <m>f</m> is continuous and absolute integrable on the interval 
              <m>(-\infty, \infty)</m> and <m>f'</m> is piecewise continuous on every finite interval. 
              If <m>f(x)\rightarrow 0</m> as <m>x\rightarrow \pm\infty,</m> then
              <ul>
                <li>    <p> <md xml:id="eq-fourer-1d" number="yes">
                  \mathscr{F}\{f'(x)\}=-i\alpha F(\alpha)
                </md>   </p>         </li>
                <li><p> With added assumptions that <m>f'</m> is continuous on <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m>, 
                  <m>f''</m> is piecewise continuous on every finite interval, and <m>f'(x)\rightarrow 0</m> 
                  as <m>x\rightarrow\pm\infty</m>, we have
                  <md xml:id="eq-fourier-2d" number="yes">
                    \mathscr{F}\{f''(x)\}=\left(-i\alpha\right)^2\mathscr{F}\{f(x)\}=-\alpha^2F(\alpha)                   
                  </md>                  
                  </p>    </li>
                 <li>  <p>Similarly, we have
                  <md>
                    \mathscr{F}\{f^{(n)}(x)\}=(-i\alpha)^nF(\alpha),
                  </md>  
                where <m>n=0,1,2,\ldots.</m>           </p>         </li> 
              </ul>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>  <p>  For <term>Fourier Cosine Transform</term> and <term> Fourier Sine Transform</term>: 
              under the same assumptions mentioned above:
            <ul>
              <li> <p> <m>\mathscr{F}_c\{f'(x)\}=\alpha \mathscr{F}_s\{f(x)\}-f(0)</m>  </p>   </li>
              <li> <p>  <m>\mathscr{F}_s\{f'(x)\}=-\alpha \mathscr{F}_c\{f(x)\}</m>      </p>      </li>
              <li><p> <m>\mathscr{F}_c\{f''(x)\}=-\alpha^2 F(\alpha)-f'(0)</m>  </p>       </li>
              <li> <p>  <m>\mathscr{F}_s\{f''(x)\}=-\alpha^2 F(\alpha)+\alpha f'(0)</m>     </p>    </li>
            </ul>             
          </p> </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </statement>      
    </remark>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p> Use a Fourier transform to solve:
          <md>
            <mrow>
            a^2\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x^2}=\frac{\partial u}{\partial t},\amp -\infty\lt x\lt\infty, t\gt 0</mrow>
            <mrow>u(x,0)=f(x),\frac{\partial u}{\partial t}\biggr|_{t=0}=g(x), \amp -\infty\lt x\lt\infty </mrow>
          </md>
          
          
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
</worksheet>

